<h2>Site survey before installation</h2>

<p>A site survey should happen before permanent mounting. The installer should inspect the roof, balcony, wall, compound, or pole location and identify anything that can block the terminal. Nairobi sites can be dense, so a few metres can matter. One side of a roof may be blocked by a neighbouring building while the other side has better sky exposure. A balcony may look convenient but may not be technically suitable.</p>

<p>The survey should also check cable routing. The cable path should avoid sharp bends, standing water, door gaps, busy walkways, hot metal edges, and places where children, staff, animals, or vehicles may damage it. Wall entry should be sealed properly. In commercial buildings, cable routing may require permission from management or coordination with maintenance staff.</p>

<p>Indoor coverage should be reviewed before the router is placed. Ask where people actually need internet. In a home, that may be the sitting room, bedrooms, study, kitchen, servant quarter, or outdoor office. In a business, it may be reception, payment desk, back office, CCTV recorder, meeting room, or guest area. A proper survey prevents the router from being placed only where the cable happens to enter.</p>

<h2>Best mounting options for Nairobi properties</h2>

<p>Roof mounting is common because it often gives the clearest sky view. The mount must be stable, safe, and waterproofed. The installer should avoid damaging iron sheets, tiles, waterproof membranes, gutters, electrical lines, or solar equipment. If the roof is fragile, steep, or inaccessible, another mount may be safer.</p>

<p>Wall mounting can work where the wall has a clear sky view and a secure fixing point. This may suit townhouses, maisonettes, and some offices. However, wall mounting should not place the terminal behind trees, high walls, or neighbouring buildings. The installer must also protect the cable and avoid making the building look untidy.</p>

<p>Pole mounting can be useful for compounds, schools, clinics, farms on the edge of Nairobi, and sites where the roof is blocked. A pole can lift the terminal above nearby obstructions, but it must be braced properly and protected from vehicle impact or tampering. For temporary or mobile use, customers should compare <a href="/amazon-leo-internet-roaming-packages-in-kenya">Amazon LEO Internet roaming packages in Kenya</a> before choosing a portable setup.</p>

