<p>For homes, the installer should test the sitting room, home office, bedrooms, and study areas. For businesses, they should test reception, payment counter, office desks, meeting rooms, and customer zones. For schools and institutions, they should test classrooms, admin areas, staff rooms, and any public-access areas. If signal is weak, the answer may be mesh Wi-Fi, wired access points, or Ethernet runs.</p>

<p>Security should be included in Wi-Fi planning. Use strong passwords and avoid sharing router admin access casually. Businesses should separate guest Wi-Fi from staff devices, payment systems, CCTV, and accounting computers. This helps critical systems stay stable when visitors or customers are online.</p>

<h2>Power backup and surge protection</h2>

<p>Power is part of internet reliability. If the terminal and router lose power, the internet stops. Nairobi users may experience outages, voltage drops, or unstable power in some buildings and estates. Homes that rely on internet for remote work or online classes should consider a UPS. Businesses and institutions may need larger backup power for the terminal, router, switches, access points, and CCTV equipment.</p>

<p>Surge protection is also important. Routers, satellite terminals, and network devices can be damaged by unstable electricity or lightning-related surges. The installer should advise on safe power points and practical protection. A customer should not spend money on a satellite kit and then run it through poor extensions or unsafe wiring.</p>

<p>Power planning should match the use case. A home may only need short backup for calls and browsing. A clinic, school, shop, or office may need longer runtime. A site that uses the connection for security cameras or payments should budget backup power from the start rather than after failures.</p>

